{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[G]Her momma picked him up in [C]south [G]Minnesota
[D7]He promised her the world but they never got that [G]far
[C]For he was last seen in that '59 [G]DeSota
[D7]When Sally was born in the black hills of [G]Dakota
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
[C]She was washed in the blood of the dying Sioux [G]nation
[D7]Raised with a proud but a wandering [G]heart
[C]And she knew that her roots were in the old [G]reservation
[D7]But she had stars in her eyes and greater [G]expectations
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
[C]No rings on her [G]fingers no [D7]bells on her [G]toes
[C]With bugs on [G]her headlights and [A7]runs in her [D7]hose
[C]Through the valley [D7]of the shadow [G]of Roosevelt's [C]nose
[G]Adios South Dakota [D7]adios Sally [G]Rose
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
[D7]They've got a national monument carved out of [G]stone
[D7]On the side of a mountain where her forefathers [G]roamed
[C]Playin' cowboys and Indians right under the [G]nose
[D7]Of Theodore Roosevelt and the sweet Sally [G]Rose
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
[C]So she left Rapid City in the blue moonlight [G]hour
[D7]With her eye on the highway and her foot on the [G]floor
[C]And turnin' the dial she was pulled by the [G]power
[D7]Of the word coming out of that broadcasting [G]tower
{end_of_verse}

